segments.text: with the different presidents and chancellors, there were no sharp changes in the way the office operated, except gradually became more demanding in terms of the high school record and so forth.
Can you think of any decisions that now, with the gift of hindsight,
that might have been made that would have improved anything?
Entirely your opinion.
Not really.
I'm going back to thinking about the changes that we made.
I think that, and this is from a management standpoint, the biggest changes that we made was instituting the Student Management Information System, SIMS, I think we call it.
in which the whole record, the admissions and records keeping thing was, I would say, computerized, to use a better word on the thing.
But it's a process in which the application, from application to graduation is now kept in a uniform records system
which you can follow the student from the very beginning until the time that they graduate.
It was quite interesting how we came about selecting a particular process because when we started doing this, we were way behind the curve, so to speak.
Many schools already had this in operation.
We opted to not go into it at the very beginning, I suppose, because we wanted to
We were satisfied.
We had a system which was working well, although it was a little bit cumbersome, but it was working well.
And we decided to let it wait a while.
And I don't recall the time, but it seemed like around 1985 was probably when we started the SYMS system at that time.
And we, at that time, visited a number of vendors, and it was interesting to see their proposals and programs and everything.
got the operation.
It took us about a year to really get the programming and everything done.
It was a major undertaking, but really well planned through the computer system, computer department, I guess it was.
And we had great cooperation and everything, and it worked, as I recall, really fairly well from the very beginning.
I don't think we had many hitches because we had
planned and worked so hard on it and laying good foundation with it.
Were there any heroes or heroines that were supporters of that decision to bring it about?
Anybody that deserves a pat on the back for supporting it?
Oh, I suppose, and for the life of me right now, I can't remember who was our biggest supporter at that particular time.
I was thinking about Dr. Gage being in the office, but I'm not sure he was in the office at that time in the Vice President's office.
Dean Gage?
Dean Gage.
He may have been there, but I do remember that we had great support as far as getting people set up to help us implement the system and everything.
I don't know who to give the credit to.
Bob Lacey, you probably know more than I.
Bob was in charge of the
getting the whole thing, coordinating the whole thing, and he did an excellent job from his standpoint on the thing.
We had good cooperation from, again, other people, as I say, getting staff set up in the SEM's office and so forth, and it worked well.
We would have never made it without it.
Who else are scattered around the campus were good supporters of the work that you and your associates?
Well, I always felt like the best support we had came from the associate dean within the college.
I forgot the term.
It wasn't academic council.
It was the academic operations committee, I believe was the term.
But that was a group I always enjoyed working with.
They gave us great support, and we try to give them great support in working with their students on the back.
Who were your favorites in that group?
Oh, goodness.
You have favorites, and you have some that are not favorites.
No, but you can mention the favorites.
I really enjoyed working with all the associate deans.
I don't know that I would want to select one over the other.
They were all great.
great people to work with and, you know, additional staff in there.
We mentioned Dale Noble a while ago.
Dale was on there and people from the academic testing office were on there.
It's just a great group to work with.
Alright, in your own personal recollection, what are some of your proudest moments of the years you worked at A&M?
I think that the
The nicest thing that I had is I had a great staff to work with the whole time I was there.
You mentioned Ms. Mitchell, Mr. Gilwood, Mr. Harvey Strigler, Ms. Luna Dean, they were the four heads of my department.
And Ms. Jean Ringer, we added the international on later on.
And they were the heads of the departments.
They were just exceptional to work with.
I think the greatest accomplishment that we had that really helped us more was getting CEMS in operation.
Because, I mean, we were floundering as far as paperwork was concerned.
It used to be when early days, if you wanted to look for a file, if you called for it and got it within 30 minutes or an hour, you were lucky.
After we got CEMS in, if we called it up and it wasn't on the screen in five or ten seconds, we thought, my goodness, it's terrible because it's so slow.
We had, again, most of the time the office was, the work which we did was just great.
I had often mentioned to people, you know, I really never looked for a, in moving to another director's admission job, because I didn't think it was any better than what I had here.
We were very fortunate in that as we grew, we had facilities to take care of the students.
We had a good building program there, but we didn't have to cut back on the enrollment too early on.
Eventually, we got to the point where we did.
And once you get to that point, it gets a whole lot tougher.
I enjoyed the freedom, which I always felt I had, to make the decisions, to run the office and everything.
I appreciate Ed's guidance there and Gary's whenever he came and took over.
a very enjoyable experience.
Again, it would be hard to name the people that you enjoy working with because there were so many.
Do you remember any particular events that you're delighted that you were there to witness?
Any kind of event?
Were involved in missions or not?
Gosh, I don't know what that would have been.
As we mentioned a while ago, I always went to graduation.
I missed one graduation, I think, in 22 years.
That was because I was sick.
But I always had a part in the graduation ceremony, and therefore I went to, whether we had three a year or whether we had seven a year, I went to every one of them.
And that's one thing I always enjoyed going to.
I don't think I...
They never feel any resentment as part of the job, but I really, I probably would have gone otherwise, I think.
But I really enjoyed that, just to see the students, the parents, and the faculty members that did too, and the joy of seeing them reach their goal and getting there as one with me and them.
Okay.
What advice would you give to current and future AM administrators about commencements?
I think the greatest thing we do is having it like we do, where the student gets their diploma, walks across the stage, gets recognition from parents, fellow classmates, and faculty.
I think this is the best thing we do.
I got my master's and doctorate from another institution, and it was a stand up and sit down affair.

I think it's just one of the nicest things we do to let the parents have the experience of seeing their son or daughter receive their diploma from an individual president of the university in this case.
And I think they leave that last official act in their relation with A&M, I think the whole family leaves there feeling good.
They've got the diploma, they don't have a facsimile, they've got the real diploma.
One of the little touches that Dr. Williams used to do that I copied wherever I went was near the end when he would ask the parents of the first generation graduates to stand.

And that was always touching because you'd see some women reaching for their handkerchief to dry a tear because I am one of those and I know how special it was to my parents that I got to go to college.
Let's see, anything that you can think of that you would change, you would have changed?
Oh, there's probably a lot of things I would have changed and done differently.
But I've always, I view it just like I did with a lot of things, kind of raising new kids.
I think I did the best I could under the circumstances with the knowledge I had at that time.
Are there any organizational changes or...
decision path changes, you'd...
There are, again, a lot of different ways you can decide on, if you're talking about the admissions process, how you can do it.
Like, where does that report now?
It reports... Is it still academic?
Still reporting to the
It's still academic.
It's still courts of the provost, and I think that's where it should be.
I think it's an academic function, and I think it should be following that.
I think it's at the provost level is probably appropriate.
I don't think it should be at the president's level.
I think he's got other things to deal with.
I think that the organization which we had with the dean and the admissions and the registrar
work fine.

There may be times when it would be better, and it depended on what the dean's function is, whether it would be better or whether to have an admissions and reporting directly to the provost and a registrar.
I didn't have any strong feelings on that.
Let's see, we're getting near the end.
Let's make believe that somebody gave you a lot of money
that you are to give to A&M a lot of money, hundreds of thousands of dollars, but you decide what it's going to be used for, what would you direct it to?
Where would you put it and for what purpose?
My personal feeling is it should probably go to scholarships.
Based on?
not necessarily academics.
I mean, academic is a priority on the thing.
But there are many students, I think, here who could do a whole lot better if they had a little financial aid.
And I would be looking to try to help those.
I think that
Are you saying more opportunity awards?
The opportunity award type scholarship, yeah.
Those students who have proven ability, lack of cash, and other support possibly on the thing, which would help those out.
That's my, not my pet peeve, but that's my concern for a lot of students.
Would you restrict it as to major?
Would you link it to any particular major?
No, I wouldn't link it to major because I've seen too many students change too many majors.
Uh, they, you know, students coming in, they just don't have enough experience to know what they want to be their major.

And, you know, on a related subject, they are, for that reason, I think there's some merit in university colleges and some other things of that nature, which you, it can keep students, I think, from feeling, quote, that they're a failure because they got in the wrong field.
Uh, having been in the wrong field myself at one time, I can have some sympathy for that.
All right, can you share with this machine any amusing flubs, goofs that you can remember that you or somebody else on the staff did that were in hindsight funny, amusing?
Something got lost for six months or somebody sent the wrong thing to somebody?
No, at the time I can think it probably was funny, I think.

I only remember one thing, I think early on I made some kind of a dumb decision about not admitting some kid, and one of my staff members convinced me I probably should have, and I remember going out the door trying to find the kid, of course I never could find him, but by that time he was long gone, I think.
Alright, Aggie stories.
Can you think of a kind of a poignant story to share?
It'll get recorded.
Stories I don't remember.
What's your favorite?
I can remember kids.
I can remember what they did.
I can remember whatever else.
Trying to remember their names was the hardest thing in the world for me.
But I can tell you, a kid can come in a year later and I can say, you came from so-and-so, you did this, you did that.
but I couldn't remember what his name was.
All right, what about, what's your favorite Aggie funny story?
You've got to have a favorite that you enjoy telling.
Well, let me go back one other instance.
I can tell you one thing, which it tells you you never know what's going to happen.
Last spring at a baseball game out here, I was going to a baseball game, a young man came up to me and he says, hello, Dr. Lay.
He says, you don't remember me.
My name is, and I think it was
His last name was Castro, and I can't even remember.
But he says that I still remember when you helped me get into A&M.
He says, and then I, we started to remember, because he had worked in the shop, and he had a shop smith, and I had a shop smith.
So we began to get that, and I remember, and he is now head of, I think, the vocational technical program for the state of Texas.
I forget what it was.
But I...
He had not met admission requirements, and he was a local boy from Bryan, and we talked for a while and said, well, we'll just see what you can do.
And that was one of my better choices, I think.
I made a good decision on that.
When you were getting down to the decision on those marginal admits,
Did you want there to be a face-to-face?
Well, yeah, I always wanted to.
There was not always that.
I realize sometimes distance would...
Right.
But I always wanted a kid to come in, and I could talk to him man-to-man, man-to-woman, whatever the case may be on the thing.
It helped when you can talk to them, I think.
It gives them a chance to present their side of the story.
A lot of times, I thought the best decision was, no, not now.
Mm-hmm.
But again, the philosophy was we're not denying you admission to A&M.
We're trying to give you a route that you can graduate from A&M.
And I think as long as we used that, for the most part, the students left reasonably satisfied.
Obviously, they wanted to come or they wouldn't have made the effort to even come for an interview.
But that's the philosophy we tried to follow.
What else should we, have we left anything out that we should have covered?
I don't know of anything.
I think we've covered a whole lot more than I thought we were going to.
Alright.
My problem is I don't remember a lot of stories on the things.
Alright, let's conclude with this.
As you look back now, those 22 years, what do you think was your responsibility?
What role do you think you and your staff played for Texas A&M?
I think that our role was to try to select a group of students who could come in to Texas A&M and be successful.
Successful in this sense was that they could receive their bachelor's degree from Texas A&M.
Any other success they have might be, that's up to them.
But what we wanted to do and what we would like to do is to select
X number of students and four years later have them receive their bachelor's degree.
That's not realistic for a lot of reasons, I think.
But we felt like our job was to try to select students who could best use the facilities which we had here.
That is, they could profit by the faculty, they could profit by living here, all the other things which go to make up the education process.
Did anybody at any other group at A&M have any responsibility more important than the one y'all had?
Well, I think that the faculty had a tremendous responsibility once we got them here.
But was it more important than y'all's?
See, I think y'all were the quality controllers.
Well, I think that we were.
I think it was our job to make a
select the group, and then somebody else takes and nurtures them and can go on from there.
How are you?
Good.
Let's quit with that.
